  <subsection permid="faM">
    <title>Consecutive Integer Problems</title>
    <example permid="Inp">
      <statement>
        <p permid="heu">
          The sum of two consecutive integers is 159.
          Find those two integers.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="DhX">
        <p permid="EXk">
          Some examples of consecutive integers are:
          <m>4</m> and <m>5</m>, <m>10</m> and <m>11</m>,
          <m>100</m> and <m>101</m>.
          Assuming the first integer is <m>x</m>,
          then the next consecutive integer is one more than <m>x</m>,
          or <m>x+1</m>.
          Their sum is given, so we can write and solve an equation:
          <md permid="zRS">
            <mrow>x+(x+1)\amp=159</mrow>
            <mrow>x+x+1\amp=159</mrow>
            <mrow>2x+1\amp=159</mrow>
            <mrow>2x\amp=158</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=79</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p permid="let">
          In summary, one integer is <m>79</m> and the other integer is <m>x+1=79+1=80</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example permid="ouy">
      <statement>
        <p permid="NlD">
          The sum of two consecutive odd integers is 160.
          Find those two integers.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="jpg">
        <p permid="RlC">
          Some examples of consecutive odd integers are:
          <m>3</m> and <m>5</m>, <m>11</m> and <m>13</m>,
          <m>105</m> and <m>107</m>.
          Assume the first integer is <m>x</m>.
          Then the next integer is two more than <m>x</m>, or <m>x+2</m>.
          Their sum is given, so we can write and solve an equation:
          <md permid="fZb">
            <mrow>x+(x+2)\amp=160</mrow>
            <mrow>x+x+2\amp=160</mrow>
            <mrow>2x+2\amp=160</mrow>
            <mrow>2x\amp=158</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=79</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p permid="xsL">
          Thus one integer is <m>79</m> and the other integer is <m>x+2=79+2=81</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise permid="UBH">
      <webwork source="BasicAlgebra/LinearEquationApplications/ConsecutiveIntegerWordProblem10.pg" seed="2"/>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection permid="LhV">
    <title>Rate-Time-Distance Application Problems</title>
    <p permid="vhZ">
      In this subsection,
      we will learn how to solve rate-time-distance application problems.
      If a person walks at the rate of <m>2</m> meters per second for a total of <m>3</m> seconds,
      he/she would walk <m>2\cdot3=6</m> meters.
      In general, we have the formula
      <me permid="Mgk">
        d=rt
      </me>
      where <m>d</m> stands for distance,
      <m>r</m> stands for rate, and <m>t</m> stands for time.
    </p>

    <example permid="AIQ">
      <statement>
        <p permid="tsM">
          A car and a bus are <m>330</m> miles apart,
          and they were driving toward each other at a constant rate.
          The car drove <m>20</m> miles faster than the bus.
          It took them <m>3</m> hours to meet.
          What was the speed of the car and the bus?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="Pwp">
        <p permid="dzU">
          When we do rate-time-distance problems,
          using a table to organize data is a good way to start.
          Assume the bus's rate is <m>b</m> miles per hour.
          This means that the car's rate is <m>b+20</m> miles per hour,
          as the bus is traveling <m>20</m> miles per hour faster than the car.
        </p>

        <table permid="NVx">
          <caption>Rate-Time-Distance Table</caption>
          <tabular permid="ucG">
            <col halign="left"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell>Rate <m>(r)</m></cell>
              <cell>Time <m>(t)</m></cell>
              <cell>Distance <m>(d=rt)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Bus</cell>
              <cell><m>b</m></cell>
              <cell><m>3</m></cell>
              <cell><m>3b</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Car</cell>
              <cell><m>b+20</m></cell>
              <cell><m>3</m></cell>
              <cell><m>3(b+20)</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

        </table>

        <p permid="JHd">
          According to the table, the bus drove <m>3b</m> miles,
          and the car drove <m>3(b+20)</m> miles.
          It's given that they drove a <em>total</em> of <m>330</m> miles.
          This means that we will set the sum of <m>3b</m> and <m>3(b+20)</m> equal to <m>330</m>,
          producing the following equation:
          <md permid="snt">
            <mrow>3b+3(b+20)\amp=330</mrow>
            <mrow>3b+3b+60\amp=330</mrow>
            <mrow>6b+60\amp=330</mrow>
            <mrow>6b\amp=270</mrow>
            <mrow>b\amp=45</mrow>
          </md>
          To determine how fast the car was traveling,
          we'll evaluate <m>b+20</m> with <m>b=45</m>:
          <md permid="YuC">
            <mrow>b+20\amp=45+20</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=65</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p permid="pOm">
          In summary, the bus was driving at a rate of <m>45</m> miles per hour and the car was driving at a rate of <m>65</m> miles per hour.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example permid="gPZ">
      <statement>
        <p permid="ZzV">
          At 12:00PM, a bicycle started riding east at the rate of <m>8</m> miles per hour.
          At 12:30PM, a car started driving east at the same spot at the speed of <m>24</m> miles per hour.
          Assuming that neither the bicycle nor the car stopped during the trip,
          when did the car catch up with the bicycle?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="vDy">
        <p permid="VVv">
          Assume it took the car <m>h</m> hours to catch up with the bicycle.
          Since the bicycle started <m>0.5</m> hours earlier than the bicycle,
          by the time the car caught up with the bicycle the bicycle had traveled <m>h+0.5</m> hours.
          We will again use a table to organize data.
        </p>

        <table permid="ajP">
          <caption>Rate-Time-Distance Table</caption>
          <tabular permid="GqY">
            <col halign="left"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell>Rate <m>(r)</m></cell>
              <cell>Time <m>(t)</m></cell>
              <cell>Distance <m>(d=rt)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Bicycle</cell>
              <cell><m>8</m></cell>
              <cell><m>h+0.5</m></cell>
              <cell><m>8(h+0.5)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Car</cell>
              <cell><m>24</m></cell>
              <cell><m>h</m></cell>
              <cell><m>24h</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

        </table>

        <p permid="CcE">
          According to the table, by the time the car caught up with the bicycle,
          the bicycle had traveled <m>8(h+0.5)</m> miles and the car had driven <m>24h</m> miles.
          Since they both traveled the same distance,
          we will set these two expressions equal to each other and solve this equation:
          <md permid="EBL">
            <mrow>8(h+0.5)\amp=24h</mrow>
            <mrow>8h+4\amp=24h</mrow>
            <mrow>8h+4\subtractright{8h}\amp=24h\subtractright{8h}</mrow>
            <mrow>4\amp=16h</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{4}{16}\amp=\frac{16h}{16}</mrow>
            <mrow>0.25\amp=h</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p permid="ijN">
          This shows that it took the car <m>0.25</m> hours
          (or <m>15</m> minutes)
          to catch up with the bicycle.
          Since the car started driving at 12:30PM, the car caught up with the bicycle at 12:45PM.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise permid="MXi">
      <webwork source="BasicAlgebra/LinearEquationApplications/DistanceWordProblemWithTable10.pg" seed="2"/>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection permid="rpe">
    <title>Investment Application Problems</title>
    <p permid="bpi">
      In this subsection,
      we will learn how to solve investment-related application problems.
      To do so, we'll first briefly review how to find a certain percent of a number.
      If we invest <m>\$1{,}000.00</m> in an account that earns <m>5\%</m> interest over a set amount of time,
      the interest we earn over that amount of time will be <m>5\%</m> of <m>$1{,}000</m>.
      To calculate this,
      we will write <m>5\%</m> as a decimal (<m>0.05</m>) and multiply <m>0.05</m> and <m>1000</m>.
      We obtain <m>0.05\cdot1000=50</m>,
      so the amount of interest is <m>\%50</m>.
    </p>

    <p permid="Hwr">
      Expanding on this, if we have <m>x</m> dollars,
      then we can represent <m>5\%</m> of that amount by multiplying <m>0.05</m> and <m>x</m>.
      Similarly, <m>5\%</m> of <m>x</m> dollars would be <m>0.05x</m> dollars.
    </p>

    <example permid="ter">
      <statement>
        <p permid="FHe">
          Greta invested <m>\$8,000</m> in two accounts.
          Over one year, Account A earned <m>2\%</m> interest and Account B earned <m>5\%</m> interest.
          Greta earned a total of <m>\$220.00</m> of interest that year.
          How much money did Greta invest in each account?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="bKH">
        <p permid="OqW">
          Assume Greta invested <m>x</m> dollars in Account A. Since she invested a total of
          <m>\$8{,}000.00</m> and invested the remaining amount in Account B, she invested <m>8000-x</m> dollars in Account B. We will again use a table to organize this data.
        </p>

        <table permid="myh">
          <caption>Table with Interest-Related Data</caption>
          <tabular permid="SFq">
            <col halign="left"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell>Interest Rate</cell>
              <cell>Amount of Money</cell>
              <cell>Amount of Interest</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Account A</cell>
              <cell><m>0.02</m></cell>
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.02x</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Account B</cell>
              <cell><m>0.05</m></cell>
              <cell><m>8000-x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.05(8000-x)</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

        </table>

        <p permid="uyf">
          According to the table, Greta earned <m>0.02x</m> dollars from Account A and
          <m>0.05(8000-x)</m> dollars from Account B. It's given that she earned a total of <m>\$220.00</m> of interest,
          so we can write and solve this equation:
          <md permid="kIU">
            <mrow>0.02x+0.05(8000-x)\amp=220</mrow>
            <mrow>0.02x+400-0.05x\amp=220</mrow>
            <mrow>-0.03x+400\amp=220</mrow>
            <mrow>-0.03x+400\subtractright{400}\amp=220\subtractright{400}</mrow>
            <mrow>-0.03x\amp=-180</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{-0.03x}{-0.03}\amp=\frac{-180}{-0.03}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=6000</mrow>
          </md>
          To determine how much she invested in Account B, we'll evaluate <m>8000-x</m> when <m>x=6000</m>:
          <md permid="QQd">
            <mrow>8000-x\amp=8000-6000</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=2000</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p permid="aFo">
          Thus Greta invested <m>\$6{,}000.00</m> in Account A and invested
          <m>\$2{,}000</m> dollars in Account B.
        </p>

        <p permid="GMx">
          To check, we want to verify that the sum of <m>2\%</m> of
          <m>\$6{,}000</m> and <m>5\%</m> of <m>\$2{,}000</m> is <m>\$220</m>:
          <md permid="wXm">
            <mrow>0.02(6000)+0.05(2000)\amp\stackrel{?}{=}220</mrow>
            <mrow>120+100\amp\stackrel{?}{=}220</mrow>
            <mrow>220\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}220</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example permid="ZlA">
      <statement>
        <p permid="lOn">
          Dave invested <m>\$10{,}000</m> in two accounts.
          After one year, Account A earned <m>2\%</m> interest,
          and Account B lost <m>5\%</m>.
          Dave lost a total of <m>\$115.00</m>.
          How much money did Dave invest in each account?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="HRQ">
        <p permid="mTG">
          Assume Dave invested <m>x</m> dollars in Account A. Since he invested a total of <m>\$10{,}000.00</m>,
          he invested <m>10000-x</m> dollars in Account B. We will again use a table to organize this data.
          Note that since Account B lost money,
          we will represent this <m>5\%</m> decrease with the decimal <m>-0.05</m>.
        </p>

        <table permid="yMz">
          <caption>Table with Interest-Related Data</caption>
          <tabular permid="eTI">
            <col halign="left"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell>Interest Rate</cell>
              <cell>Amount of Money</cell>
              <cell>Amount of Interest</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Account A</cell>
              <cell><m>0.02</m></cell>
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.02x</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Account B</cell>
              <cell><m>-0.05</m></cell>
              <cell><m>10000-x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-0.05(10000-x)</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

        </table>

        <p permid="TaP">
          According to the table, Dave earned <m>0.02x</m> dollars from Account A, and earned <m>-0.04(10000-x)</m> dollars (or lost
          <m>0.04(10000-x)</m> dollars) from Account B. It's given that he lost a total of <m>\$190.00</m> of interest,
          so we can write and solve this equation:
          <md permid="dev">
            <mrow>0.02x+(-0.04(10000-x))\amp=-190</mrow>
            <mrow>0.02x+(-400+0.04x)\amp=-190</mrow>
            <mrow>0.02x-400+0.04x\amp=-190</mrow>
            <mrow>0.06x-400\amp=-190</mrow>
            <mrow>0.06x-400\addright{400}\amp=-190\addright{400}</mrow>
            <mrow>0.06x\amp=210</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{0.06x}{0.06}\amp=\frac{210}{0.06}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=3500</mrow>
          </md>
          To calculate the amount in Account B, we'll evaluate <m>10000-x</m> for <m>x=3500</m>:
          <md permid="JlE">
            <mrow>10000-x\amp=10000-3500</mrow>
            <mrow>6500</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p permid="zhY">
          Dave invested <m>\$3{,}500.00</m> in Account A, and invested
          <m>\$6{,}500</m> dollars in Account B.
        </p>

        <p permid="fph">
          To check, we want to verify that the total of gaining <m>2\%</m> of
          <m>\$3{,}500</m> and losing <m>4\%</m> of <m>\$6{,}500</m> is <m>\$220</m>:
          <md permid="psN">
            <mrow>0.02(3500)-0.04(6500)\amp\stackrel{?}{=}-190</mrow>
            <mrow>70-260\amp\stackrel{?}{=}-190</mrow>
            <mrow>-190\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}-190</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise permid="FsJ">
      <webwork source="BasicAlgebra/LinearEquationApplications/InterestWordProblemWithTable20.pg" seed="2"/>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection permid="Xwn">
    <title>Mixture Application Problems</title>
    <p permid="nDA">
      In this subsection,
      we will learn how to solve mixture application problems.
      They are very similar to interest-related problems.
    </p>

    <example permid="lzS">
      <statement>
        <p permid="RVw">
          A chemist has 40 ounces of <m>8\%</m> saline
          (salt water).
          She wants to mix in some <m>2\%</m> saline to make a solution with <m>6\%</m> saline.
          How much <m>2\%</m> saline should she mix into the <m>8\%</m> saline?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="nYZ">
        <p permid="Lwq">
          We will use the following strategy to write an equation: The amount of pure salt in the <m>8\%</m> solution and the <m>2\%</m> solution,
          after mixed up,
          must be equal to the amount of pure salt in the <m>6\%</m> solution.
          Assume she needs to mix in 40 ounces of <m>2\%</m> solution.
          A table can organize data nicely.
        </p>

        <table permid="LaR">
          <caption>Table with Data in Mixed Solutions</caption>
          <tabular permid="Xpj">
            <col halign="left"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell>Purity</cell>
              <cell>Amount of Solution (in oz)</cell>
              <cell>Amount of Pure Salt (in oz)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>8\%</m> Solution</cell>
              <cell><m>0.08</m></cell>
              <cell><m>40</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.08\cdot40=3.2</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>2\%</m> Solution</cell>
              <cell><m>0.02</m></cell>
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.02x</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>6\%</m> Solution</cell>
              <cell><m>0.06</m></cell>
              <cell><m>x+40</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.06(x+40)</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

        </table>

        <p permid="rDz">
          According to the table,
          the <m>8\%</m> solution will contribute <m>3.2</m> oz of pure salt into the mixture,
          and the <m>2\%</m> solution will contribute <m>0.02x</m> oz.
          The <m>6\%</m> solution has a total of <m>0.06(x+40)</m> oz of pure salt.
          We can write and solve this equation:
          <md permid="VzW">
            <mrow>3.2+0.02x\amp=0.06(x+40)</mrow>
            <mrow>3.2+0.02x\amp=0.06x+2.4</mrow>
            <mrow>3.2+0.02x\subtractright{0.02x}\amp=0.06x+2.4\subtractright{0.02x}</mrow>
            <mrow>3.2\amp=0.04x+2.4</mrow>
            <mrow>3.2\subtractright{2.4}\amp=0.04x+2.4\subtractright{2.4}</mrow>
            <mrow>0.8\amp=0.04x</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{0.8}{0.04}\amp=\frac{0.04x}{0.04}</mrow>
            <mrow>20\amp=x</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p permid="XKI">
          To make a solution with <m>6\%</m> saline,
          the chemist needs to mix <m>20</m> oz of <m>2\%</m> saline into the <m>8\%</m> saline.
        </p>

        <p permid="DRR">
          Now, we can substitute <m>20</m> into <m>x</m> in the table to check our solution:
        </p>

        <table permid="ria">
          <caption>Table with Data in Mixed Solutions</caption>
          <tabular permid="Dws">
            <col halign="left"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell>Purity</cell>
              <cell>Amount of Solution (in oz)</cell>
              <cell>Amount of Pure Salt (in oz)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>8\%</m> Solution</cell>
              <cell><m>0.08</m></cell>
              <cell><m>40</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.08\cdot40=3.2</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>2\%</m> Solution</cell>
              <cell><m>0.02</m></cell>
              <cell><m>20</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.02\cdot20=0.4</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>6\%</m> Solution</cell>
              <cell><m>0.06</m></cell>
              <cell><m>60</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.06\cdot60=3.6</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

        </table>

      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise permid="dVt">
      <webwork source="BasicAlgebra/LinearEquationApplications/MixedSolutionWordProblemWithTable20.pg" seed="2"/>
    </exercise>

    <p permid="TKJ">
      This type of application problem can be extended to other types of mixtures,
      like people, coffee, money, etc.
      We will look at a few more examples.
    </p>

    <example permid="RHb">
      <statement>
        <p permid="ycF">
          A coffee shop has 30 pounds of dark roast coffee,
          which sells for <m>\$12.00</m> per pound.
          It also has some light roast coffee,
          which sells for <m>\$8.00</m> per pound.
          The coffee shop plans to mix some light roast coffee into the dark roast coffee and sell the mixture for <m>\$9.20</m> per pound.
          How many pounds of light roast coffee should be mixed in?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="Ugi">
        <p permid="jZa">
          This problem can be solved with the same method as the saline mixture problem above.
          Assume the coffee shop will mix in <m>p</m> pounds of light roast coffee.
          We will use a table to organize this data.
        </p>

        <table permid="jDB">
          <caption>Table with Data in Mixed Coffee</caption>
          <tabular permid="vRT">
            <col halign="left"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell>Price per Pound (in Dollars)</cell>
              <cell>Amount of Coffee (in Pounds)</cell>
              <cell>Total Value (in Dollars)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Dark Roast Coffee</cell>
              <cell><m>12</m></cell>
              <cell><m>30</m></cell>
              <cell><m>12\cdot30=360</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Light Roast Coffee</cell>
              <cell><m>8</m></cell>
              <cell><m>p</m></cell>
              <cell><m>8p</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Mixture</cell>
              <cell><m>9.2</m></cell>
              <cell><m>p+30</m></cell>
              <cell><m>9.2(p+30)</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

        </table>

        <p permid="Qgj">
          According to the table,
          the dark roast coffee's total value is <m>\$360.00</m>,
          and the light roast coffee's total value is <m>8p</m> dollars.
          After they are mixed, the total value will be <m>9.2(p+30)</m> dollars.
          Now we can write and solve this equation:
          <md permid="BHf">
            <mrow>360+8p\amp=9.2(p+30)</mrow>
            <mrow>360+8p\amp=9.2p+276</mrow>
            <mrow>360+8p\subtractright{8p}\amp=9.2p+276\subtractright{8p}</mrow>
            <mrow>360\amp=1.2p+276</mrow>
            <mrow>360\subtractright{276}\amp=1.2p+276\subtractright{276}</mrow>
            <mrow>84\amp=1.2p</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{84}{1.2}\amp=\frac{1.2p}{1.2}</mrow>
            <mrow>70\amp=p</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p permid="wns">
          To make the mixture worth <m>\$9.20</m> per pound,
          the coffee shop needs to mix <m>70</m> pounds of light roast coffee into the dark roast coffee.
        </p>

        <p permid="cuB">
          Now, we can substitute <m>70</m> into <m>x</m> in the table to check our solution:
        </p>

        <table permid="PKK">
          <caption>Table with Data in Mixed Coffee</caption>
          <tabular permid="bZc">
            <col halign="left"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell>Price per Pound (in Dollars)</cell>
              <cell>Amount of Coffee (in Pounds)</cell>
              <cell>Total Value (in Dollars)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Dark Roast Coffee</cell>
              <cell><m>12</m></cell>
              <cell><m>30</m></cell>
              <cell><m>12\cdot30=360</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>South Campus</cell>
              <cell><m>8</m></cell>
              <cell><m>70</m></cell>
              <cell><m>8\cdot70=560</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Mixture</cell>
              <cell><m>9.2</m></cell>
              <cell><m>100</m></cell>
              <cell><m>9.2\cdot100=920</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

        </table>

      </solution>
    </example>

    <example permid="xOk">
      <statement>
        <p permid="ejO">
          A college used to have a north campus with <m>2,000</m> students and a south campus with <m>500</m> students.
          The north campus had <m>5\%</m> LGBT (Lesbian/Gay/Bisexual/Transgender) students.
          After those two campuses merged,
          the combined campus had <m>5.2\%</m> LGBT students.
          What percent of LGBT students did the south campus have?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="Anr">
        <p permid="IBK">
          Assume the south campus had <m>p</m> percent LGBT students.
          We will use a table to organize data.
        </p>

        <table permid="Igl">
          <caption>Table with Data in Mixed Population</caption>
          <tabular permid="UuD">
            <col halign="left"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell>Percent of LGBT Students</cell>
              <cell>Number of All Students</cell>
              <cell>Number of LGBT Students</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>North Campus</cell>
              <cell><m>0.05</m></cell>
              <cell><m>2000</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.05\cdot2000=100</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>South Campus</cell>
              <cell><m>p</m></cell>
              <cell><m>500</m></cell>
              <cell><m>500p</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Merged Campus</cell>
              <cell><m>0.052</m></cell>
              <cell><m>2000+500=2500</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.052\cdot2500=130</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

        </table>

        <p permid="oIT">
          According to the table, the north campus had <m>100</m> LGBT students,
          and the south campus had <m>500p</m> LGBT students.
          Since the merged campus had <m>130</m> LGBT students,
          we can write and solve this equation:
          <md permid="hOo">
            <mrow>100+500p\amp=130</mrow>
            <mrow>100+500p\subtractright{100}\amp=130\subtractright{100}</mrow>
            <mrow>500p\amp=30</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{500p}{500}\amp=\frac{30}{500}</mrow>
            <mrow>p\amp=0.06</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p permid="UQc">
          Solution: The south campus had <m>6\%</m> LGBT students.
        </p>

        <p permid="AXl">
          Now, we can substitute <m>0.06</m> into <m>p</m> in the table to check our solution:
        </p>

        <table permid="onu">
          <caption>Table with Data in Mixed Population</caption>
          <tabular permid="ABM">
            <col halign="left"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell>Percent of LGBT Students</cell>
              <cell>Number of All Students</cell>
              <cell>Number of LGBT Students</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>North Campus</cell>
              <cell><m>0.05</m></cell>
              <cell><m>2000</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.05\cdot2000=100</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>South Campus</cell>
              <cell><m>0.06</m></cell>
              <cell><m>500</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.06\cdot500=30</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Merged Campus</cell>
              <cell><m>0.052</m></cell>
              <cell><m>2000+500=2500</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0.052\cdot2500=130</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>

        </table>

      </solution>
    </example>
